  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="NA125-kiḷavi">itu varaivu nīṭṭippa vāṟṟāḷāya talaiviyait tōḻi vaṟpuṟuttiyatu.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante comforted HER who did not have the strength when [HE] delayed the marriage.</p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA125">
<l>            iraitē reṇkiṉ pakuvā yēṟṟai</l>
<l>            koṭuvarip puṟṟam vāyppa vāṅki</l>
<l>            nallarā naṭuṅka vuraṟik kolla</l>
<l>            ṉūtulaik kuruki ṉuḷḷuyirt takaḻu</l>
<l>            naṭunāḷ varuta lañcutum yāmeṉa </l>
<l>            varaintuvara lirakkuva māyi ṉammalai</l>
<l>            naṉṉāḷ vatuvai kūṭi nīṭiṉṟu</l>
<l>            nammoṭu celvarmaṟ ṟōḻi mella</l>
<l>            vēṅkaik kaṇṇiya reruteṟi kaḷamar</l>
<l>            nilaṅkaṇ ṭaṉṉa vakaṉkaṭ pācaṟai </l>
<l>            meṉṟiṉai neṭumpōr purimār</l>
<l>            tuñcukaḷi ṟeṭuppuntam peruṅka ṉāṭṭē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent">If we beg [his] marrying [us and then] coming,</l>
<l rend="indent2">saying “we fear [your] coming at midnight,</l>
<l rend="indent3">when the broad-mouthed male of the anteater searching for prey</l>
<l rend="indent3">bends to reach the anthill with curved stripes,</l>
<l rend="indent3">roars for the good snake to shiver [and] digs [it] out,</l>
<l rend="indent3">sighing inside like the bellows the smith blows on the furnace”,</l>
<l>he will certainly go with us, friend, without it being long</l>
<l rend="indent">that he meets [his] bride on a good day, on our mountain,</l>
<l rend="indent">– to his land of big stones, where the sleeping elephant bull awakes,</l>
<l rend="indent">when<note place="foot">This is no very satisfactory construction of <term xml:lang="ta">purimār</term>, -<term xml:lang="ta">mār</term> being supposed to give a final infinitive.</note> those wearing chaplets of Vēṅkai in soft [shoots?]<note place="foot">Is this the way to integrate <term xml:lang="ta">mella</term>?</note> make</l>
<l rend="indent">long heaps of soft millet on the green rocks in a wide area,</l>
<l rend="indent2">as if one sees the ground</l>
<l rend="indent3">of those on the threshing-floor throwing the bull.<note place="foot">Here the point of the comparison is not clear. Is the harvested ripe corn of the millet put on the rocks in order to dry? And does this look like the threshing-floor for rice found in the lowland? But what is the relation to the bull-baiting festival? And where does the awakening elephant bull come into the picture?</note></l>
        </lg>
         </div>
